                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>Possibly completed by the author <persName role="scr" cert="medium"
                                    xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Abū-al-Barakāt bin Muḥammd Naṣr
                                    Allāh</persName> on behalf of <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"
                                    >Mīr Sayyid Iltifāt</persName> in <origPlace cert="medium"
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502">Awadh</origPlace>
                                in regnal year 23 of Shāh ‘Ālam, corresponding to <origDate
                                    calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1747-08-17">7 Sha‘bān 1160 (17
                                    Aug 1747)</origDate>.</p></origin>
                        <provenance><p>Thereafter accessioned into the royal library of the Kings of
                                    <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502"
                                    >Awadh</placeName>, possibly held in the Moti Mahal Palace, then
                                later transferred to the Qaisarbagh Palace as indicated by a dated
                                library notation on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, and
                                seal impressions of <persName type="person" role="fmo seal"
                                    key="person_265857376" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/265857376"
                                    >Nāṣir al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r. 1827–1837)</persName>,
                                    <persName role="fmo" key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                                    ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006">Amjad ‘Alī
                                    Shāh (b. 1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, and <persName
                                    type="person" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167"
                                    role="fmo seal" key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh (b. 1822,
                                    r. 1847–1856)</persName>. Presumably looted during India's First
                                War of Independence, when British soldiers ransacked the Qaisarbagh
                                palace and library on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1858-03-15"
                                    >15 March 1858</date> (see Wolseley's memoir).</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied"
                                    key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel
                                    George William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> who served in
                                    <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                                    key="place_7000208">India</placeName>
                                <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to
                                    1867</date>, latterly as Commissioner in <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535"
                                    key="place_7001535">Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a
                                thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts, from which the <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British Museum</orgName>
                                purchased 352 from his widow, <persName key="person_f8470"
                                    role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton (1817–1893)</persName>, now
                                held in the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British
                                    Library</orgName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance><p>
                                <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">
                                    Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName>,
                                purchased the remainder in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868"
                                    >1868</date> for <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552"
                                    key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh
                                Hall, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                                    key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                                    change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                                    >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                                    type="corporation" role="rps"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
